# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cell-nucleus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] Along with the 28S and 5.8S rRNA in eukaryotes, the **18S rRNA** was early identified as integral structural element of ribosomes which were first characterized by their sedimentation properties and named according to measured Svedberg units.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] Given its ubiquitous presence in eukaryotic life, the evolution of the 18S rRNA was soon proposed as marker for phylogenetic studies to resolve the evolution of eukaryotes.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] The **18S ribosomal RNA** is the structural RNA of the small subunit in the eukaryotic cytoplasmic ribosome.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] The genomic sequence of the 18S rRNA is organized in a group with the 28S and 5.8S rRNA, separated and flanked by the ITS-1, ITS-2 and ETS spacer regions.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] These regions of ribosomal DNA (rDNA) are present with several hundred copies in the active genome, clustered in nucleolus organizer regions (NORs).
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] In ribosome biogenesis, these genes are transcribed together by the RNA polymerase I and are processed in the nucleolus structure of the nucleus.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] The length of the 18S rRNA varies considerably in the eukaryotic phylogenetic tree, corresponding to a range of 16S-19S in Svedberg units, with the average length commonly given as around 2000 nucleotides.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] The 18S rRNA of humans has a length of 1869 nucleotides.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] The universal presence of the **18S rRNA** in eukaryotes and generally high degree of conservation in evolution allow the construction of universal primers for DNA amplification by polymerase chain reaction.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] The possible applications mirror molecular methods involving 16S rRNA of prokaryotes.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] Primers binding in highly conserved regions of the 18S rRNA are an important marker for biodiversity screening, allowing the amplification of unspecified or random targets from environmental samples as well as uncharacterized specimens from collections for DNA sequencing.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] Subsequent sequence alignment covering the less strictly conserved segments then allows the assignment of a sample to biologic clades.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] In the case of 18S rRNA, retrieval of DNA is improved by the abundance of repeating sequences of the rDNA within eukaryotic cells, promoting the sensitivity of the analysis.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] Multiple properties of the genomic sequence of the 18S rRNA have established it as an important marker gene for large-scale phylogenetic analysis and the reconstruction of the metazoan tree of life.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] The integral role in formation and function of the ribosome is a key cause for its omnipresence in eukaryotic life.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] Meanwhile, the gene maintains a high degree of conservation under a persistent selective pressure in all living beings, highlighting its potential for comparison between distantly related clades.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] Early studies utilizing the 18S rRNA sequence constructed the first large-scale phylogenetic trees of the metazoa.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] Evidence from further studies led to the creation of several important clades, such as the Ecdysozoa and Lophotrochozoa.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] During the latter part of the 2000s, and with increased numbers of taxa included into molecular phylogenies, however, two problems became apparent.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] First, there are prevailing sequencing impediments in representatives of certain taxa, such as the mollusk classes Solenogastres and Tryblidia, selected bivalve taxa, and the enigmatic crustacean class Remipedia.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] Failure to obtain 18S sequences of single taxa is considered a common phenomenon but is rarely ever reported.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] Secondly, in contrast to initially high hopes, 18S cannot resolve nodes at all taxonomic levels and its efficacy varies considerably among clades.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] This has been discussed as an effect of rapid ancient radiation within short periods.
[src:cell-nucleus/18s-ribosomal-rna] Multigene analyses are currently thought to give more reliable results for tracing deep branching events in Metazoa but 18S still is extensively used in phylogenetic analyses.
[src:cell-nucleus/28s-ribosomal-rna] Combined with 5.8S rRNA to the 5' side, it is the eukaryotic nuclear homologue of the prokaryotic 23S and mitochondrial 16S ribosomal RNAs.
[src:cell-nucleus/28s-ribosomal-rna] The genes coding for 28S rRNA are referred to as 28S rDNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/28s-ribosomal-rna] The comparison of the sequences from these genes are sometimes used in molecular analysis to construct phylogenetic trees, for example in protists, fungi, insects, arachnids, tardigrades, and vertebrates.
[src:cell-nucleus/28s-ribosomal-rna] The 28S rRNA is typically 4000–5000 nt long.
[src:cell-nucleus/28s-ribosomal-rna] Some eukaryotes cleave 28S rRNA into two parts before assembling both into the ribosome, a phenomenon termed the "hidden break".
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] In molecular biology, the **5.8S ribosomal RNA** (**5.8S rRNA**) is a non-coding RNA component of the large subunit of the eukaryotic ribosome and so plays an important role in protein translation.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] It is transcribed by RNA polymerase I as part of the 45S precursor that also contains 18S and 28S rRNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] Its function is thought to be in ribosome translocation.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] It is also known to form covalent linkage to the p53 tumour suppressor protein.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] 5.8S rRNA can be used as a reference gene for miRNA detection.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S ribosomal RNA is used to better understand other rRNA processes and pathways in the cell.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S rRNA is homologous to the 5' end of non-eukaryotic LSU rRNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] In eukaryotes, the insertion of ITS2 breaks LSU rRNA into 5.8S and 28S rRNAs.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] Some flies have their 5.8 rRNA further split into two pieces at the 3' end, forming what is called 5.8S, ITS2a, and 2S.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] L567.5 rRNA structure is approximately 150 nucleotides in size and it consists of plenty of folded strands, some of which are presumed to be single stranded.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] This ribosomal RNA, along with the 28S and 5S rRNA as well as 46 ribosomal proteins, forms the ribosomal large subunit (LSU).
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S rRNA is initially transcribed along with the 18S and 28S rRNA in the 45S preribosomal RNA, along with the ITS 1 and ITS 2 (Internal transcribed spacer) and a 5’ and 3’ ETS (External transcribed spacer).
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S rRNA is located between the two ITS regions, with ITS1 separating it from the 18S rRNA in the 5' direction, and ITS2 separating it from the 28S rRNA in the 3' direction.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The ITS and ETS are cleaved away during rRNA maturation.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] This is accomplished through a continuous cleavage pathway performed by both endonuclease and exonuclease enzymes, cutting the spacers at specific locations.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] In molecular biology, the **five-prime cap** (**5′ cap**) is a specially altered nucleotide on the 5′ end of some primary transcripts such as precursor messenger RNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] In eukaryotes, the main form is **mRNA capping**, a highly regulated process that uses 7-methylguanosine, vital in the creation of stable and mature messenger RNA able to undergo translation during protein synthesis.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Mitochondrial mRNA and chloroplastic mRNA are not capped.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] When an RNA is made by a RNA polymerase (RNAP), it has a triphosphate group on its 5' end due to the use of nucleoside triphosphates (NTP, pppN) by the RNAP.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] In eukaryotes, the exposed ppp end is "capped" by a guanine soon after it is freed from the RNAP, forming the 5' cap.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Due to how it formed, the cap connects to mRNA via an unusual 5′ to 5′ triphosphate linkage.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] This guanosine is methylated on the 7 position directly after capping *in vivo* by a methyltransferase.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] The result is a 7-methylguanylate (m7G) cap.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Cap-0, mRNA with only the m7G cap, is the basic cap structure for eukaryotic mRNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Its structure is written as m7GpppN: m7G, connected to a string of three phosphate groups, then to any other nucleotide.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] The first and second transcribed nucleotides can also be 2' O-methylated (N → Nm), leading to the Cap-1 and Cap-2 structures, respectively.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Cap-1 has a methylated 2′-hydroxy group on the first ribose sugar[m7G ppp Nm-], while cap-2 has methylated 2′-hydroxy groups on the first two ribose sugars [m7G ppp Nm p Nm-], shown on the right.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] This is more common in higher eukaryotes and thought to be part of the innate immune system to recognize mRNAs from other organisms.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] The choice of whether to make these modifications vary by organism and the starting bases of the mRNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] This strategy is also adopted by some viruses that infect eukaryotes.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] In all organisms, mRNA molecules can be decapped in a process known as messenger RNA decapping.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] This is usually followed by degradation of the mRNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] The starting point for capping with 7-methylguanylate is the unaltered 5′ end of an RNA molecule, which terminates at a triphosphate group.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] This features a final nucleotide followed by three phosphate groups attached to the 5′ carbon.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] The capping process is initiated before the completion of transcription, as the nascent pre-mRNA (ppp(-5′)N[pN]n) is being synthesized.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] GTP is added to the terminal bisphosphate by mRNA guanylyltransferase (GTase), losing a pyrophosphate from the GTP substrate in the process.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] The above describes the canonical capping process involving a TPase, GTase, and a MTase, arriving at Cap-0.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Cap-1 and Cap-2 can be produced from Cap-0 with 2'-O-methylation by a mRNA (nucleoside-2'-O-)-methyltransferase (2'-O-MTase).
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Further modification is also possible: for example, if the nearest cap-adjacent nucleotide is 2′-*O*-ribose methyl-adenosine (i.e.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] (m7G)ppp(Am)[pN]n), it can be further methylated at the N6 methyl position to form *N*6-methyladenosine, resulting in 5′(m7G)ppp(N6Am)[pN]n.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] For capping with 7-methylguanylate, the capping enzyme complex (CEC) binds to RNA polymerase II before transcription starts.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] As soon as the 5′ end of the new transcript emerges from RNA polymerase II, the CEC carries out the capping process (this kind of mechanism ensures capping, as with polyadenylation).
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] The enzymes for capping can only bind to RNA polymerase II, ensuring specificity to only these transcripts, which are almost entirely mRNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Promotion of 5′ proximal intron excision.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Nuclear export of RNA is regulated by the cap binding complex (CBC), which binds exclusively to 7-methylguanylate-capped RNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] The CBC is then recognized by the nuclear pore complex and exported.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Once in the cytoplasm after the pioneer round of translation, the CBC is replaced by the translation factors eIF4E and eIF4G of the eIF4F complex.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] This complex is then recognized by other translation initiation machinery including the ribosome.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Capping with 7-methylguanylate prevents 5′ degradation in multiple ways.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] First, degradation of the mRNA by 5′ exonucleases (which are abundant in the nucleus) is prevented by chemically looking like a 3′ end.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Second, the CBC and eIF4E/eIF4G block the access of decapping enzymes to the cap.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Additional cap-binding proteins also contribute.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] This increases the half-life of the mRNA, essential in eukaryotes as the export and translation processes take significant time.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] The mechanism of 5′ proximal intron excision promotion is not well understood, but the 7-methylguanylate cap appears to loop around and interact with the spliceosome in the splicing process, promoting intron excision.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Decapping of a 7-methylguanylate-capped mRNA is catalyzed by the decapping complex made up of at least Dcp1 and Dcp2, which must compete with eIF4E to bind the cap.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Thus the 7-methylguanylate cap is a marker of an actively translating mRNA and is used by cells to regulate mRNA half-lives in response to new stimuli.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Undesirable mRNAs are sent to P-bodies for temporary storage or decapping, the details of which are still being resolved.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] The corresponding enzyme activity is m7G(5')pppN diphosphatase, which produces the products m7Gp and ppN-RNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Viruses that infect eukaryotes employ a variety of stretegies to form caps that the host would recognize.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Some encode the canonical trio of enzymes, occasionally in combination with a 2'-O-MTase (e.g. vaccinia virus).
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] There are also ones that use more different options.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] For example, picornavirus has its RdRP build RNAs starting with a protein, which acts as a cap.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] In addition, some of the Mimiviridae carry a variant of eIF4F for their own use.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] The viral version specifically recognizes m7GpppAm-mRNA, the kind made by other viral proteins, and is not downregulated in times of stress like the host version.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Eukaryotic small nuclear RNAs contain unique 5′-caps.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Sm-class snRNAs are found with 2,2,7-trimethylguanosine (m3G) caps, while Lsm-class snRNAs are found with monomethyl caps.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Both are linked to the 5' end of the RNA via a triphosphate (ppp) linkage (in 5'-5' orientation in the case of m3G), like the mRNA cap.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] In bacteria, and potentially also in higher organisms, some RNAs are capped with NAD+, NADH, or 3′-dephospho-coenzyme A (dpCoA).
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Unlike the eukaryotic caps, the bacterial caps are linked to 5' end of the RNA using a regular monophosphate (p) linkage; they internally contain a diphosphate linkage, however.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] The mechanism of capping with NAD(+/H) or dpCoA is different.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Capping with these groups is accomplished through an "ab initio capping mechanism," in which NAD(+/H) or dpCoA serves as a "non-canonical initiating nucleotide" (NCIN) for transcription initiation by RNA polymerase and thereby directly is incorporated into the RNA product.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] This is due to their structual similarity with ATP.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Both bacterial RNA polymerase and eukaryotic RNA polymerase II are able to carry out this "ab initio capping mechanism" *in vitro*.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] Capping with NAD(+/H) or dpCoA is targeted by promoter sequence.
[src:cell-nucleus/5-cap] NCIN capping occurs only at promoters that have certain sequences at and immediately upstream of the transcription start site and therefore occurs only for RNAs synthesized from certain promoters.
[src:cell-nucleus/aaas-gene] Aladin is a component of the nuclear pore complex, to which it is attached by nucleoporin NDC1.
[src:cell-nucleus/aaas-gene] Mutant aladin causes selective failure of nuclear protein import and hypersensitivity to oxidative stress.
[src:cell-nucleus/aaas-gene] Mutant aladin also causes decreased nuclear import of aprataxin, a repair protein for single-strand breaks, and DNA ligase I, employed in DNA base excision repair.
[src:cell-nucleus/aaas-gene] These decreases in DNA repair proteins may increase the susceptibility of cells to oxidative stress by allowing accumulation of oxidative DNA damages that trigger cell death.
[src:cell-nucleus/aaas-gene] Mutations in the AAAS gene are responsible for Triple A syndrome (also known as Allgrove Syndrome).
[src:cell-nucleus/aaas-gene] Triple-A syndrome is an autosomal recessive neuroendocrinological disease.
[src:cell-nucleus/aaas-gene] Aladin is also employed in specific oocyte meiotic stages, including spindle assembly and spindle positioning.
[src:cell-nucleus/aaas-gene] Female mice homozygously null for aladin are sterile.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] The **Acantharia** are a group of radiolarian protozoa, distinguished mainly by their strontium sulfate skeletons.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Acantharians are heterotrophic marine microplankton that range in size from about 200 microns in diameter up to several millimeters.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Some acantharians have photosynthetic endosymbionts and hence are considered mixotrophs.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Acantharian skeletons are composed of strontium sulfate, SrSO4, in the form of mineral celestine crystal.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Celestine is named for the delicate blue colour of its crystals, and is the heaviest mineral in the ocean.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] The denseness of their celestite ensures acantharian shells function as mineral ballast, resulting in fast sedimentation to bathypelagic depths.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] High settling fluxes of acantharian cysts have been observed at times in the Iceland Basin and the Southern Ocean, as much as half of the total gravitational organic carbon flux.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] The strontium sulfate crystals are secreted by vacuoles surrounding each spicule or spine.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Acantharians are unique among marine organisms for their ability to biomineralize strontium sulfate as the main component of their skeletons.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] However, unlike other radiolarians whose skeletons are made of silica, acantharian skeletons do not fossilize, primarily because strontium sulfate is very scarce in seawater and the crystals dissolve after the acantharians die.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] The arrangement of the spines is very precise, and is described by what is called the Müllerian law in terms of lines of latitude and longitude – the spines lie on the intersections between five of the former, symmetric about an equator, and eight of the latter, spaced uniformly.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Each line of longitude carries either two *tropical* spines or one *equatorial* and two *polar* spines, in alternation.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] The cell cytoplasm is divided into two regions: the endoplasm and the ectoplasm.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] The endoplasm, at the core of the cell, contains the main organelles, including many nuclei, and is delineated from the ectoplasm by a capsular wall made of a microfibril mesh.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] In symbiotic species, the algal symbionts are maintained in the endoplasm.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] The ectoplasm consists of cytoplasmic extensions used for prey capture and also contains food vacuoles for prey digestion.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] The ectoplasm is surrounded by a periplasmic cortex, also made up of microfibrils, but arranged into twenty plates, each with a hole through which one spicule projects.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] The cortex is linked to the spines by contractile myonemes, which assist in buoyancy control by allowing the ectoplasm to expand and contract, increasing and decreasing the total volume of the cell.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] The way that the spines are joined at the center of the cell varies and is one of the primary characteristics by which acantharians are classified.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] The skeletons are made up of either ten diametric or twenty radial spicules.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Diametric spicules cross the center of the cell, whereas radial spicules terminate at the center of the cell where they either form a tight or flexible junction depending on species.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Acantharians with diametric spicules or loosely attached radial spicules are able to rearrange or shed spicules and form cysts.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] The morphological classification system roughly agrees with phylogenetic trees based on the alignment of ribosomal RNA genes, although the groups are mostly polyphyletic.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Holacanthida seems to have evolved first and includes molecular clades A, B, and D.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Chaunacanthida evolved second and includes only one molecular clade, clade C.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Arthracanthida and Symphacanthida, which have the most complex skeletons, evolved most recently and constitute molecular clades E and F.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Many acantharians, including some in clade B (Holacanthida) and all in clades E & F (Symphiacanthida and Arthracanthida), host single-celled algae within their inner cytoplasm (endoplasm).
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] By participating in this photosymbiosis, acantharians are essentially mixotrophs: they acquire energy through both heterotrophy and autotrophy.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] The relationship may make it possible for acantharians to be abundant in low-nutrient regions of the oceans and may also provide extra energy necessary to maintain their elaborate strontium sulfate skeletons.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] It is hypothesized that the acantharians provide the algae with nutrients (N & P) that they acquire by capturing and digesting prey in return for sugar that the algae produces during photosynthesis.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] It is not known, however, whether the algal symbionts benefit from the relationship or if they are simply being exploited and then digested by the acantharians.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Symbiotic Holacanthida acantharians host diverse symbiont assemblages, including several genera of dinoflagellates (*Pelagodinium*, *Heterocapsa*, *Scrippsiella*, *Azadinium*) and a haptophyte (*Chrysochromulina*).
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Clade E & F acantharians have a more specific symbiosis and primarily host symbionts from the haptophyte genus *Phaeocystis*, although they sometimes also host *Chrysochromulina* symbionts.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Clade F acantharians simultaneously host multiple species and strains of *Phaeocystis* and their internal symbiont community does not necessarily match the relative availability of potential symbionts in the surrounding environment.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] The mismatch between internal and external symbiont communities suggests that acantharians can be selective in choosing symbionts and probably do not continuously digest and recruit new symbionts, and maintain symbionts for extended periods of time instead.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Earlier diverging clades are able to shed their spines and form cysts, which are often referred to as reproductive cysts.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Reproduction is thought to take place by formation of swarmer cells (formerly referred to as "spores"), which may be flagellate, and cysts have been observed to release these swarmers.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Non-encysted cells have also been seen releasing swarmers in laboratory conditions.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Not all life cycle stages have been observed, however, and no one has witnessed the fusion of swarmers to produce a new acantharian.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Cysts are often found in sediment traps and it is therefore believed that the cysts help acantharians sink into deep water.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Genetic data and some imaging suggests that non-cyst-forming acantharians may also sink to deep water to release swarmers.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Releasing swarmer cells in deeper water may improve the survival chances of juveniles.
[src:cell-nucleus/acantharea] Study of these organisms has been hampered mainly by an inability to "close the lifecycle" and maintain these organisms in culture through successive generations.
[src:cell-nucleus/acrosome] The **acrosome** is an organelle that develops over the anterior (front) half of the head in the spermatozoa (sperm cells) of humans and many other animals.
[src:cell-nucleus/acrosome] It is a cap-like structure derived from the Golgi apparatus.
[src:cell-nucleus/acrosome] In placental mammals, the acrosome contains degradative enzymes (including hyaluronidase and acrosin).
[src:cell-nucleus/acrosome] These enzymes break down the outer membrane of the ovum, called the zona pellucida, allowing the haploid nucleus in the sperm cell to join with the haploid nucleus in the ovum.
[src:cell-nucleus/acrosome] This shedding of the acrosome, known as the acrosome reaction, can be stimulated *in vitro* by substances that a sperm cell may encounter naturally, such as progesterone or follicular fluid, as well as the more commonly used calcium ionophore A23187.
[src:cell-nucleus/acrosome] This can be done to serve as a positive control when assessing the acrosome reaction of a sperm sample by flow cytometry or fluorescence microscopy.
[src:cell-nucleus/acrosome] This is usually done after staining with a fluoresceinated lectin such as FITC-PNA, FITC-PSA, FITC-ConA, or fluoresceinated antibody such as FITC-CD46.
[src:cell-nucleus/acrosome] In the case of globozoospermia (sperm with round heads), the Golgi apparatus is not transformed into the *acrosome*, causing male infertility.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The **cell nucleus** (from Latin **nucleus* or *nuculeus** 'kernel, seed'; pl.: **nuclei**) is a membrane-bound organelle found in eukaryotic cells.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Eukaryotic cells usually have a single nucleus, but a few cell types, such as mammalian red blood cells, have no nuclei, and a few others including osteoclasts have many.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The main structures making up the nucleus are the nuclear envelope, a double membrane that encloses the entire organelle and isolates its contents from the cellular cytoplasm; and the nuclear matrix, a network within the nucleus that adds mechanical support.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The cell nucleus contains nearly all of the cell's genome.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Nuclear DNA is often organized into multiple chromosomes – long strands of DNA dotted with various proteins, such as histones, that protect and organize the DNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The genes within these chromosomes are structured in such a way to promote cell function.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nucleus maintains the integrity of genes and controls the activities of the cell by regulating gene expression.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Because the nuclear envelope is impermeable to large molecules, nuclear pores are required to regulate nuclear transport of molecules across the envelope.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The pores cross both nuclear membranes, providing a channel through which larger molecules must be actively transported by carrier proteins while allowing free movement of small molecules and ions.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Movement of large molecules such as proteins and RNA through the pores is required for both gene expression and the maintenance of chromosomes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Although the interior of the nucleus does not contain any membrane-bound subcompartments, a number of nuclear bodies exist, made up of unique proteins, RNA molecules, and particular parts of the chromosomes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The best-known of these is the nucleolus, involved in the assembly of ribosomes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The cell nucleus contains most of the cell's genetic material in the form of multiple linear DNA molecules organized into chromosomes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Each human cell contains roughly two meters of DNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Throughout most of the cell cycle this DNA exists in a DNA-protein complex known as chromatin, while during cell division the chromatin forms the well-defined chromosomes familiar from a karyotype.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] A small portion of the cell's genes are instead located in the mitochondria.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Euchromatin is the less compact DNA form, and contains genes that are frequently expressed by the cell.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The other type, heterochromatin, is the more compact form, and contains DNA that is infrequently transcribed.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] During interphase the chromatin organizes itself into discrete individual patches, called *chromosome territories*.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Active genes, which are generally found in the euchromatic region of the chromosome, tend to be located towards the chromosome's territory boundary.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Antibodies to certain types of chromatin organization, in particular, nucleosomes, have been associated with a number of autoimmune diseases, such as systemic lupus erythematosus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] These are known as anti-nuclear antibodies (ANA) and have also been observed in concert with multiple sclerosis as part of general immune system dysfunction.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nucleus contains nearly all of the cell's DNA, surrounded by a network of fibrous intermediate filaments called the nuclear matrix, and is enveloped in a double membrane called the nuclear envelope.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nuclear envelope separates the fluid inside the nucleus, called the nucleoplasm, from the rest of the cell.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The size of the nucleus is correlated to the size of the cell, and this ratio is reported across a range of cell types and species.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In eukaryotes the nucleus in many cells typically occupies 10% of the cell volume.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nucleus is the largest organelle in animal cells.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In human cells, the diameter of the nucleus is approximately six micrometres (μm).
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nuclear envelope consists of two membranes, an inner and an outer nuclear membrane, perforated by nuclear pores.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Together, these membranes serve to separate the cell's genetic material from the rest of the cell contents, and allow the nucleus to maintain an environment distinct from the rest of the cell.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Despite their close apposition around much of the nucleus, the two membranes differ substantially in shape and contents.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The inner membrane surrounds the nuclear content, providing its defining edge.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Embedded within the inner membrane, various proteins bind the intermediate filaments that give the nucleus its structure.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The outer membrane encloses the inner membrane, and is continuous with the adjacent endoplasmic reticulum membrane.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] As part of the endoplasmic reticulum membrane, the outer nuclear membrane is studded with ribosomes that are actively translating proteins across membrane.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The space between the two membranes is called the perinuclear space, and is continuous with the endoplasmic reticulum lumen.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In a mammalian nuclear envelope there are between 3000 and 4000 nuclear pore complexes (NPCs) perforating the envelope.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Each NPC contains an eightfold-symmetric ring-shaped structure at a position where the inner and outer membranes fuse.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The number of NPCs can vary considerably across cell types; small glial cells only have about a few hundred, with large Purkinje cells having around 20,000.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The NPC provides selective transport of molecules between the nucleoplasm and the cytosol.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nuclear pore complex is composed of approximately thirty different proteins known as nucleoporins.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The pores are about 60–80 million daltons in molecular mass and consist of around 50 (in yeast) to several hundred proteins (in vertebrates).
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The pores are 100 nm in total diameter; however, the gap through which molecules freely diffuse is only about 9 nm wide, due to the presence of regulatory systems within the center of the pore.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This size selectively allows the passage of small water-soluble molecules while preventing larger molecules, such as nucleic acids and larger proteins, from inappropriately entering or exiting the nucleus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] These large molecules must be actively transported into the nucleus instead.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Attached to the ring is a structure called the **nuclear basket** that extends into the nucleoplasm, and a series of filamentous extensions that reach into the cytoplasm.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Both structures serve to mediate binding to nuclear transport proteins.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Most proteins, ribosomal subunits, and some RNAs are transported through the pore complexes in a process mediated by a family of transport factors known as karyopherins.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Those karyopherins that mediate movement into the nucleus are also called importins, whereas those that mediate movement out of the nucleus are called exportins.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Most karyopherins interact directly with their cargo, although some use adaptor proteins.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Steroid hormones such as cortisol and aldosterone, as well as other small lipid-soluble molecules involved in intercellular signaling, can diffuse through the cell membrane and into the cytoplasm, where they bind nuclear receptor proteins that are trafficked into the nucleus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] There they serve as transcription factors when bound to their ligand; in the absence of a ligand, many such receptors function as histone deacetylases that repress gene expression.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In animal cells, two networks of intermediate filaments provide the nucleus with mechanical support: The nuclear lamina forms an organized meshwork on the internal face of the envelope, while less organized support is provided on the cytosolic face of the envelope.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Both systems provide structural support for the nuclear envelope and anchoring sites for chromosomes and nuclear pores.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nuclear lamina is composed mostly of lamin proteins.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Like all proteins, lamins are synthesized in the cytoplasm and later transported to the nucleus interior, where they are assembled before being incorporated into the existing network of nuclear lamina.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Lamins found on the cytosolic face of the membrane, such as emerin and nesprin, bind to the cytoskeleton to provide structural support.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Lamins are also found inside the nucleoplasm where they form another regular structure, known as the *nucleoplasmic veil*, that is visible using fluorescence microscopy.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The actual function of the veil is not clear, although it is excluded from the nucleolus and is present during interphase.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Lamin structures that make up the veil, such as LEM3, bind chromatin and disrupting their structure inhibits transcription of protein-coding genes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Like the components of other intermediate filaments, the lamin monomer contains an alpha-helical domain used by two monomers to coil around each other, forming a dimer structure called a coiled coil.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Two of these dimer structures then join side by side, in an antiparallel arrangement, to form a tetramer called a *protofilament*.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Eight of these protofilaments form a lateral arrangement that is twisted to form a ropelike *filament*.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] These filaments can be assembled or disassembled in a dynamic manner, meaning that changes in the length of the filament depend on the competing rates of filament addition and removal.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Mutations in lamin genes leading to defects in filament assembly cause a group of rare genetic disorders known as *laminopathies*.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The most notable laminopathy is the family of diseases known as progeria, which causes the appearance of premature aging in those with the condition.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The exact mechanism by which the associated biochemical changes give rise to the aged phenotype is not well understood.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nucleolus is the largest of the discrete densely stained, membraneless structures known as nuclear bodies found in the nucleus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] It forms around tandem repeats of rDNA, DNA coding for ribosomal RNA (rRNA).
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] These regions are called nucleolar organizer regions (NOR).
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The main roles of the nucleolus are to synthesize rRNA and assemble ribosomes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The structural cohesion of the nucleolus depends on its activity, as ribosomal assembly in the nucleolus results in the transient association of nucleolar components, facilitating further ribosomal assembly, and hence further association.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This model is supported by observations that inactivation of rDNA results in intermingling of nucleolar structures.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In the first step of ribosome assembly, a protein called RNA polymerase I transcribes rDNA, which forms a large pre-rRNA precursor.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This is cleaved into two large rRNA subunits – 5.8S, and 28S, and a small rRNA subunit 18S.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The transcription, post-transcriptional processing, and assembly of rRNA occurs in the nucleolus, aided by small nucleolar RNA (snoRNA) molecules, some of which are derived from spliced introns from messenger RNAs encoding genes related to ribosomal function.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The assembled ribosomal subunits are the largest structures passed through the nuclear pores.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Transcription of the rDNA occurs either in the FC or at the FC-DFC boundary, and, therefore, when rDNA transcription in the cell is increased, more FCs are detected.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Most of the cleavage and modification of rRNAs occurs in the DFC, while the latter steps involving protein assembly onto the ribosomal subunits occur in the GC.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Speckles are subnuclear structures that are enriched in pre-messenger RNA splicing factors and are located in the interchromatin regions of the nucleoplasm of mammalian cells.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] At the fluorescence-microscope level, they appear as irregular, punctate structures, which vary in size and shape, and when examined by electron microscopy, they are seen as clusters of interchromatin granules.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Speckles are dynamic structures, and both their protein and RNA-protein components can cycle continuously between speckles and other nuclear locations, including active transcription sites.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Speckles can work with p53 as enhancers of gene activity to directly enhance the activity of certain genes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Moreover, speckle-associating and non-associating p53 gene targets are functionally distinct.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Studies on the composition, structure and behaviour of speckles have provided a model for understanding the functional compartmentalization of the nucleus and the organization of the gene-expression machinery splicing snRNPs and other splicing proteins necessary for pre-mRNA processing.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Because of a cell's changing requirements, the composition and location of these bodies changes according to mRNA transcription and regulation via phosphorylation of specific proteins.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The splicing speckles are also known as nuclear speckles (nuclear specks), splicing factor compartments (SF compartments), interchromatin granule clusters (IGCs), and B snurposomes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] B snurposomes are found in the amphibian oocyte nuclei and in *Drosophila melanogaster* embryos.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] B snurposomes appear alone or attached to the Cajal bodies in the electron micrographs of the amphibian nuclei.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] A nucleus typically contains between one and ten compact structures called Cajal bodies or coiled bodies (CB), whose diameter measures between 0.2 μm and 2.0 μm depending on the cell type and species.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] When seen under an electron microscope, they resemble balls of tangled thread and are dense foci of distribution for the protein coilin.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] CBs are involved in a number of different roles relating to RNA processing, specifically small nucleolar RNA (snoRNA) and small nuclear RNA (snRNA) maturation, and histone mRNA modification.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Similar to Cajal bodies are Gemini of Cajal bodies, or gems, whose name is derived from the Gemini constellation in reference to their close "twin" relationship with CBs.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Gems are similar in size and shape to CBs, and in fact are virtually indistinguishable under the microscope.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Unlike CBs, gems do not contain small nuclear ribonucleoproteins (snRNPs), but do contain a protein called survival of motor neuron (SMN) whose function relates to snRNP biogenesis.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Gems are believed to assist CBs in snRNP biogenesis, though it has also been suggested from microscopy evidence that CBs and gems are different manifestations of the same structure.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Later ultrastructural studies have shown gems to be twins of Cajal bodies with the difference being in the coilin component; Cajal bodies are SMN positive and coilin positive, and gems are SMN positive and coilin negative.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Beyond the nuclear bodies first described by Santiago Ramón y Cajal above (e.g., nucleolus, nuclear speckles, Cajal bodies) the nucleus contains a number of other nuclear bodies.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] These include polymorphic interphase karyosomal association (PIKA), promyelocytic leukaemia (PML) bodies, and paraspeckles.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Although little is known about a number of these domains, they are significant in that they show that the nucleoplasm is not a uniform mixture, but rather contains organized functional subdomains.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Other subnuclear structures appear as part of abnormal disease processes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] For example, the presence of small intranuclear rods has been reported in some cases of nemaline myopathy.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This condition typically results from mutations in actin, and the rods themselves consist of mutant actin as well as other cytoskeletal proteins.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] PIKA domains, or polymorphic interphase karyosomal associations, were first described in microscopy studies in 1991.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Their function remains unclear, though they were not thought to be associated with active DNA replication, transcription, or RNA processing.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] They have been found to often associate with discrete domains defined by dense localization of the transcription factor PTF, which promotes transcription of small nuclear RNA (snRNA).
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Promyelocytic leukemia protein (PML-nuclear bodies) are spherical bodies found scattered throughout the nucleoplasm, measuring around 0.1–1.0 μm.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] They are known by a number of other names, including nuclear domain 10 (ND10), Kremer bodies, and PML oncogenic domains.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] PML-nuclear bodies are named after one of their major components, the promyelocytic leukemia protein (PML).
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] They are often seen in the nucleus in association with Cajal bodies and cleavage bodies.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Pml-/- mice, which are unable to create PML-nuclear bodies, develop normally without obvious ill effects, showing that PML-nuclear bodies are not required for most essential biological processes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Discovered by Fox et al. in 2002, paraspeckles are irregularly shaped compartments in the interchromatin space of the nucleus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] First documented in HeLa cells, where there are generally 10–30 per nucleus, paraspeckles are now known to also exist in all human primary cells, transformed cell lines, and tissue sections.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Their name is derived from their distribution in the nucleus; the "para" is short for parallel and the "speckles" refers to the splicing speckles to which they are always in close proximity.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Paraspeckles sequester nuclear proteins and RNA and thus appear to function as a molecular sponge that is involved in the regulation of gene expression.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Furthermore, paraspeckles are dynamic structures that are altered in response to changes in cellular metabolic activity.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] They are transcription dependent and in the absence of RNA Pol II transcription, the paraspeckle disappears and all of its associated protein components (PSP1, p54nrb, PSP2, CFI(m)68, and PSF) form a crescent shaped perinucleolar cap in the nucleolus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This phenomenon is demonstrated during the cell cycle.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In the cell cycle, paraspeckles are present during interphase and during all of mitosis except for telophase.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] During telophase, when the two daughter nuclei are formed, there is no RNA Pol II transcription so the protein components instead form a perinucleolar cap.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Perichromatin fibrils are visible only under electron microscope.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] They are located next to the transcriptionally active chromatin and are hypothesized to be the sites of active pre-mRNA processing.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Clastosomes are small nuclear bodies (0.2–0.5 μm) described as having a thick ring-shape due to the peripheral capsule around these bodies.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This name is derived from the Greek *klastos* (κλαστός), broken and *soma* (σῶμα), body.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Clastosomes are not typically present in normal cells, making them hard to detect.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] They form under high proteolytic conditions within the nucleus and degrade once there is a decrease in activity or if cells are treated with proteasome inhibitors.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The scarcity of clastosomes in cells indicates that they are not required for proteasome function.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Osmotic stress has also been shown to cause the formation of clastosomes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] These nuclear bodies contain catalytic and regulatory subunits of the proteasome and its substrates, indicating that clastosomes are sites for degrading proteins.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nucleus provides a site for genetic transcription that is segregated from the location of translation in the cytoplasm, allowing levels of gene regulation that are not available to prokaryotes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The main function of the cell nucleus is to control gene expression and mediate the replication of DNA during the cell cycle.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nuclear envelope allows control of the nuclear contents, and separates them from the rest of the cytoplasm where necessary.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This regulatory mechanism occurs in the case of glycolysis, a cellular pathway for breaking down glucose to produce energy.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Hexokinase is an enzyme responsible for the first step of glycolysis, forming glucose-6-phosphate from glucose.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] At high concentrations of fructose-6-phosphate, a molecule made later from glucose-6-phosphate, a regulator protein removes hexokinase to the nucleus, where it forms a transcriptional repressor complex with nuclear proteins to reduce the expression of genes involved in glycolysis.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In order to control which genes are being transcribed, the cell separates some transcription factor proteins responsible for regulating gene expression from physical access to the DNA until they are activated by other signaling pathways.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This prevents even low levels of inappropriate gene expression.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] A nuclear localisation signal on the NF-κB protein allows it to be transported through the nuclear pore and into the nucleus, where it stimulates the transcription of the target genes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The compartmentalization allows the cell to prevent translation of unspliced mRNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Eukaryotic mRNA contains introns that must be removed before being translated to produce functional proteins.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The splicing is done inside the nucleus before the mRNA can be accessed by ribosomes for translation.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Without the nucleus, ribosomes would translate newly transcribed (unprocessed) mRNA, resulting in malformed and nonfunctional proteins.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] It has been found that replication happens in a localised way in the cell nucleus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In the S phase of interphase of the cell cycle; replication takes place.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Contrary to the traditional view of moving replication forks along stagnant DNA, a concept of *replication factories* emerged, which means replication forks are concentrated towards some immobilised 'factory' regions through which the template DNA strands pass like conveyor belts.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Gene expression first involves transcription, in which DNA is used as a template to produce RNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In the case of genes encoding proteins, that RNA produced from this process is messenger RNA (mRNA), which then needs to be translated by ribosomes to form a protein.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] As ribosomes are located outside the nucleus, mRNA produced needs to be exported.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Since the nucleus is the site of transcription, it also contains a variety of proteins that either directly mediate transcription or are involved in regulating the process.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Newly synthesized mRNA molecules are known as primary transcripts or pre-mRNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] They must undergo post-transcriptional modification in the nucleus before being exported to the cytoplasm; mRNA that appears in the cytoplasm without these modifications is degraded rather than used for protein translation.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The three main modifications are 5' capping, 3' polyadenylation, and RNA splicing.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] While in the nucleus, pre-mRNA is associated with a variety of proteins in complexes known as heterogeneous ribonucleoprotein particles (hnRNPs).
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Addition of the 5' cap occurs co-transcriptionally and is the first step in post-transcriptional modification.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The 3' poly-adenine tail is only added after transcription is complete.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] RNA splicing, carried out by a complex called the spliceosome, is the process by which introns, or regions of DNA that do not code for protein, are removed from the pre-mRNA and the remaining exons connected to re-form a single continuous molecule.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This process normally occurs after 5' capping and 3' polyadenylation but can begin before synthesis is complete in transcripts with many exons.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Many pre-mRNAs can be spliced in multiple ways to produce different mature mRNAs that encode different protein sequences.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This process is known as alternative splicing, and allows production of a large variety of proteins from a limited amount of DNA.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The entry and exit of large molecules from the nucleus is tightly controlled by the nuclear pore complexes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Although small molecules can enter the nucleus without regulation, macromolecules such as RNA and proteins require association karyopherins called importins to enter the nucleus and exportins to exit.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] "Cargo" proteins that must be translocated from the cytoplasm to the nucleus contain short amino acid sequences known as nuclear localization signals, which are bound by importins, while those transported from the nucleus to the cytoplasm carry nuclear export signals bound by exportins.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The ability of importins and exportins to transport their cargo is regulated by GTPases, enzymes that hydrolyze the molecule guanosine triphosphate (GTP) to release energy.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The key GTPase in nuclear transport is Ran, which is bound to either GTP or GDP (guanosine diphosphate), depending on whether it is located in the nucleus or the cytoplasm.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Whereas importins depend on RanGTP to dissociate from their cargo, exportins require RanGTP in order to bind to their cargo.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Nuclear import depends on the importin binding its cargo in the cytoplasm and carrying it through the nuclear pore into the nucleus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Inside the nucleus, RanGTP acts to separate the cargo from the importin, allowing the importin to exit the nucleus and be reused.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Nuclear export is similar, as the exportin binds the cargo inside the nucleus in a process facilitated by RanGTP, exits through the nuclear pore, and separates from its cargo in the cytoplasm.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Specialized export proteins exist for translocation of mature mRNA and tRNA to the cytoplasm after post-transcriptional modification is complete.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This quality-control mechanism is important due to these molecules' central role in protein translation.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Mis-expression of a protein due to incomplete excision of exons or mis-incorporation of amino acids could have negative consequences for the cell; thus, incompletely modified RNA that reaches the cytoplasm is degraded rather than used in translation.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] During its lifetime, a nucleus may be broken down or destroyed, either in the process of cell division or as a consequence of apoptosis (the process of programmed cell death).
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] During these events, the structural components of the nucleus — the envelope and lamina — can be systematically degraded.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In most cells, the disassembly of the nuclear envelope marks the end of the prophase of mitosis.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] However, this disassembly of the nucleus is not a universal feature of mitosis and does not occur in all cells.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Some unicellular eukaryotes (e.g., yeasts) undergo so-called closed mitosis, in which the nuclear envelope remains intact.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In closed mitosis, the daughter chromosomes migrate to opposite poles of the nucleus, which then divides in two.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The cells of higher eukaryotes, however, usually undergo open mitosis, which is characterized by breakdown of the nuclear envelope.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The daughter chromosomes then migrate to opposite poles of the mitotic spindle, and new nuclei reassemble around them.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] At a certain point during the cell cycle in open mitosis, the cell divides to form two cells.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In order for this process to be possible, each of the new daughter cells must have a full set of genes, a process requiring replication of the chromosomes as well as segregation of the separate sets.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This occurs by the replicated chromosomes, the sister chromatids, attaching to microtubules, which in turn are attached to different centrosomes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The sister chromatids can then be pulled to separate locations in the cell.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In many cells, the centrosome is located in the cytoplasm, outside the nucleus; the microtubules would be unable to attach to the chromatids in the presence of the nuclear envelope.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Therefore, the early stages in the cell cycle, beginning in prophase and until around prometaphase, the nuclear membrane is dismantled.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Likewise, during the same period, the nuclear lamina is also disassembled, a process regulated by phosphorylation of the lamins by protein kinases such as the CDC2 protein kinase.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Towards the end of the cell cycle, the nuclear membrane is reformed, and around the same time, the nuclear lamina are reassembled by dephosphorylating the lamins.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] However, in dinoflagellates, the nuclear envelope remains intact, the centrosomes are located in the cytoplasm, and the microtubules come in contact with chromosomes, whose centromeric regions are incorporated into the nuclear envelope (the so-called closed mitosis with extranuclear spindle).
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In many other protists (e.g., ciliates, sporozoans) and fungi, the centrosomes are intranuclear, and their nuclear envelope also does not disassemble during cell division.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Apoptosis is a controlled process in which the cell's structural components are destroyed, resulting in death of the cell.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Changes associated with apoptosis directly affect the nucleus and its contents, for example, in the condensation of chromatin and the disintegration of the nuclear envelope and lamina.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The destruction of the lamin networks is controlled by specialized apoptotic proteases called caspases, which cleave the lamin proteins and, thus, degrade the nucleus' structural integrity.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Lamin cleavage is sometimes used as a laboratory indicator of caspase activity in assays for early apoptotic activity.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Cells that express mutant caspase-resistant lamins are deficient in nuclear changes related to apoptosis, suggesting that lamins play a role in initiating the events that lead to apoptotic degradation of the nucleus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Inhibition of lamin assembly itself is an inducer of apoptosis.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nuclear envelope acts as a barrier that prevents both DNA and RNA viruses from entering the nucleus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Some viruses require access to proteins inside the nucleus in order to replicate and/or assemble.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] DNA viruses, such as herpesvirus replicate and assemble in the cell nucleus, and exit by budding through the inner nuclear membrane.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This process is accompanied by disassembly of the lamina on the nuclear face of the inner membrane.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Initially, it has been suspected that immunoglobulins in general and autoantibodies in particular do not enter the nucleus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Now there is a body of evidence that under pathological conditions (e.g. lupus erythematosus) IgG can enter the nucleus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Most eukaryotic cell types usually have a single nucleus, but some have no nuclei, while others have several.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This can result from normal development, as in the maturation of mammalian red blood cells, or from faulty cell division.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] An anucleated cell contains no nucleus and is, therefore, incapable of dividing to produce daughter cells.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The best-known anucleated cell is the mammalian red blood cell, or erythrocyte, which also lacks other organelles such as mitochondria, and serves primarily as a transport vessel to ferry oxygen from the lungs to the body's tissues.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Erythrocytes mature through erythropoiesis in the bone marrow, where they lose their nuclei, organelles, and ribosomes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nucleus is expelled during the process of differentiation from an erythroblast to a reticulocyte, which is the immediate precursor of the mature erythrocyte.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The presence of mutagens may induce the release of some immature "micronucleated" erythrocytes into the bloodstream.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Anucleated cells can also arise from flawed cell division in which one daughter lacks a nucleus and the other has two nuclei.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In flowering plants, this condition occurs in sieve tube elements.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Multinucleated cells contain multiple nuclei.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Most acantharean species of protozoa and some fungi in mycorrhizae have naturally multinucleated cells.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Other examples include the intestinal parasites in the genus *Giardia*, which have two nuclei per cell.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Ciliates have two kinds of nuclei in a single cell, a somatic macronucleus and a germline micronucleus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In humans, skeletal muscle cells, also called myocytes and syncytium, become multinucleated during development; the resulting arrangement of nuclei near the periphery of the cells allows maximal intracellular space for myofibrils.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Other multinucleate cells in the human are osteoclasts a type of bone cell.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Multinucleated and binucleated cells can also be abnormal in humans; for example, cells arising from the fusion of monocytes and macrophages, known as giant multinucleated cells, sometimes accompany inflammation and are also implicated in tumor formation.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] A number of dinoflagellates are known to have two nuclei.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Unlike other multinucleated cells these nuclei contain two distinct lineages of DNA: one from the dinoflagellate and the other from a symbiotic diatom.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] As the major defining characteristic of the eukaryotic cell, the nucleus's evolutionary origin has been the subject of much speculation.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Four major hypotheses have been proposed to explain the existence of the nucleus, although none have yet earned widespread support.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The first model known as the "syntrophic model" proposes that a symbiotic relationship between the archaea and bacteria created the nucleus-containing eukaryotic cell.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] (Organisms of the Archaeal and Bacterial domains have no cell nucleus.) It is hypothesized that the symbiosis originated when ancient archaea similar to modern methanogenic archaea, invaded and lived within bacteria similar to modern myxobacteria, eventually forming the early nucleus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This theory is analogous to the accepted theory for the origin of eukaryotic mitochondria and chloroplasts, which are thought to have developed from a similar endosymbiotic relationship between proto-eukaryotes and aerobic bacteria.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] One possibility is that the nuclear membrane arose as a new membrane system following the origin of mitochondria in an archaebacterial host.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nuclear membrane may have served to protect the genome from damaging reactive oxygen species produced by the protomitochondria.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The archaeal origin of the nucleus is supported by observations that archaea and eukarya have similar genes for certain proteins, including histones.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Observations that myxobacteria are motile, can form multicellular complexes, and possess kinases and G proteins similar to eukarya, support a bacterial origin for the eukaryotic cell.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] A second model proposes that proto-eukaryotic cells evolved from bacteria without an endosymbiotic stage.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This model is based on the existence of modern Planctomycetota bacteria that possess a nuclear structure with primitive pores and other compartmentalized membrane structures.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] A similar proposal states that a eukaryote-like cell, the hypothetical *chronocyte*, evolved first and phagocytosed archaea and bacteria to generate the nucleus and the eukaryotic cell.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The most controversial model, known as *viral eukaryogenesis*, posits that the membrane-bound nucleus, along with other eukaryotic features, originated from the infection of a prokaryote by a virus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The suggestion is based on similarities between eukaryotes and viruses such as linear DNA strands, mRNA capping, and tight binding to proteins (analogizing histones to viral envelopes).
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] One version of the proposal suggests that the nucleus evolved in concert with phagocytosis to form an early cellular "predator".
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Another variant proposes that eukaryotes originated from early archaea infected by poxviruses, on the basis of observed similarity between the DNA polymerases in modern poxviruses and eukaryotes.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] It has been suggested that the unresolved question of the evolution of sex could be related to the viral eukaryogenesis hypothesis.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nucleus was the first organelle to be discovered.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] What is most likely the oldest preserved drawing dates back to the early microscopist Antonie van Leeuwenhoek (1632–1723).
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] He observed a "lumen", the nucleus, in the red blood cells of salmon.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Unlike mammalian red blood cells, those of other vertebrates still contain nuclei.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The nucleus was also described by Franz Bauer in 1804 and in more detail in 1831 by Scottish botanist Robert Brown in a talk at the Linnean Society of London.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Brown was studying orchids under the microscope when he observed an opaque area, which he called the "areola" or "nucleus", in the cells of the flower's outer layer.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] He did not suggest a potential function.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In 1838, Matthias Schleiden proposed that the nucleus plays a role in generating cells, thus he introduced the name "**cytoblast**" ("cell builder").
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] He believed that he had observed new cells assembling around "cytoblasts".
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Franz Meyen was a strong opponent of this view, having already described cells multiplying by division and believing that many cells would have no nuclei.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The idea that cells can be generated de novo, by the "cytoblast" or otherwise, contradicted work by Robert Remak (1852) and Rudolf Virchow (1855) who decisively propagated the new paradigm that cells are generated solely by cells ("*Omnis cellula e cellula*").
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The function of the nucleus remained unclear.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Between 1877 and 1878, Oscar Hertwig published several studies on the fertilization of sea urchin eggs, showing that the nucleus of the sperm enters the oocyte and fuses with its nucleus.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This was the first time it was suggested that an individual develops from a (single) nucleated cell.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This was in contradiction to Ernst Haeckel's theory that the complete phylogeny of a species would be repeated during embryonic development, including generation of the first nucleated cell from a "monerula", a structureless mass of primordial protoplasm ("Urschleim").
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Therefore, the necessity of the sperm nucleus for fertilization was discussed for quite some time.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] However, Hertwig confirmed his observation in other animal groups, including amphibians and molluscs.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] Eduard Strasburger produced the same results for plants in 1884.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] This paved the way to assign the nucleus an important role in heredity.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] In 1873, August Weismann postulated the equivalence of the maternal and paternal germ *cells* for heredity.
[src:cell-nucleus/cell-nucleus] The function of the nucleus as carrier of genetic information became clear only later, after mitosis was discovered and the Mendelian rules were rediscovered at the beginning of the 20th century; the chromosome theory of heredity was therefore developed.
